          content:
            'The Genpei War (1180–1185 CE), a conflict between the Taira and Minamoto warrior clans for control of Japan, ended with the decisive Minamoto victory at the naval battle of Dan-no-Ura in 1185. Minamoto no Yoritomo, who had directed the campaign from his base at Kamakura in eastern Japan, now held military dominance over the entire archipelago. Rather than moving to the capital and attempting to govern through the existing court structure as the Taira had done, Yoritomo established a separate administrative center (bakufu, or "tent government") at Kamakura — physically distant from the imperial court in Kyoto and organized around the warrior class\'s own values and relationships.\n\nIn 1192, Yoritomo was granted the title Sei-i Taishōgun (Barbarian-Subduing Generalissimo), institutionalizing what would become the shogunate: a military government that would, in various forms, rule Japan for nearly 700 years. The emperor and his court continued to exist in Kyoto, performing their ritual and ceremonial functions, but real political and military power now resided with the shogun and the warrior class (bushi or samurai) organized around him. This dual structure — a legitimate but powerless emperor and an effective but formally subordinate military ruler — became the characteristic form of Japanese governance.\n\nYoritomo\'s death in 1199 quickly exposed the fragility of his personal leadership: his sons proved weak, and effective control passed to the Hōjō family, Yoritomo\'s in-laws, who exercised power as regents to the shogun — an ironic echo of the Fujiwara regency over the emperor. The Hōjō regency nonetheless governed with considerable competence, including the remarkable response to the Mongol invasions of 1274 and 1281 CE, when fleets sent by Kublai Khan were repelled — partly by Japanese resistance, but decisively by typhoons that the Japanese called kamikaze (divine winds), interpreting the storms as evidence of divine protection.\n\nThe Kamakura period saw the emergence of new forms of Buddhism better suited to the warrior class and to ordinary people than the complex esoteric traditions that had flourished at the Heian court. Zen Buddhism, introduced from China by monks such as Eisai and Dōgen, offered a direct, practice-centered path to enlightenment that resonated with warrior values of discipline, simplicity, and present-moment awareness. Pure Land Buddhism (Jōdo), taught by Hōnen and Shinran, offered salvation through faith in Amida Buddha alone — accessible to anyone regardless of learning or social position — and won enormous popular followings.\n\nThe Kamakura shogunate eventually collapsed under the pressure of accumulated resentments: warrior families who had fought the Mongols received little compensation (there was no conquered territory to distribute), the Hōjō monopolized power at the expense of other great families, and Emperor Go-Daigo led a determined effort to restore direct imperial rule. The Kemmu Restoration (1333) briefly returned power to the court, but Ashikaga Takauji, a general who had helped overthrow the Hōjō, turned against Go-Daigo and established a new military government in Kyoto — the Ashikaga shogunate — opening the next period of Japanese history.',
