          content:
            'The brief Momoyama period (roughly 1568–1600 CE) takes its name from Hideyoshi\'s castle at Fushimi (Momoyama) south of Kyoto, and describes the cultural epoch spanning Nobunaga\'s seizure of Kyoto through the Battle of Sekigahara. It was a period of extravagant aesthetic ambition: the great castle complexes of Azuchi, Osaka, and Fushimi, decorated with gold-leaf screens and massive painted walls, expressed the confident wealth and power of the new warlord class. The intimate scale of the Ashikaga-era tea ceremony co-existed with the spectacular grandeur of Momoyama architecture — warlords patronizing both the restrained and the magnificent with equal enthusiasm.\n\nThe period also saw the peak of European engagement with Japan. Following the Portuguese introduction of firearms in 1543, Jesuit missionaries arrived in 1549, beginning what Japanese historians call the "Christian century." Francis Xavier, the first Jesuit to reach Japan, was impressed by Japanese intellectual engagement and cultural sophistication and reported optimistically to Rome. Christianity spread with remarkable speed in parts of Kyushu and among some daimyo who welcomed the trade connections associated with Jesuit missionaries. By the late 16th century, perhaps 150,000–300,000 Japanese had converted, and several prominent daimyo had been baptized.\n\nOda Nobunaga\'s patronage of the Jesuits was essentially instrumental: he saw Christianity as a counterweight to Buddhist institutional power. But Toyotomi Hideyoshi\'s attitude shifted dramatically. In 1587, alarmed by reports that Christian daimyo were forcing conversions and contemplating the transfer of land to the Church, he issued an expulsion edict for missionaries — though enforcement was initially lax. The 1597 martyrdom of twenty-six Christians (both European missionaries and Japanese converts) crucified at Nagasaki signaled a hardening policy. The Tokugawa shogunate would complete the suppression, turning the persecution of Christianity into a systematic and bloody process.\n\nThe Momoyama aesthetic — characterized by bold color, gold backgrounds, monumental scale, and confident display — contrasted sharply with the restrained, asymmetrical quietude of Zen-influenced Muromachi art. Both traditions survived into the Tokugawa period, with the flamboyant decorative tradition finding expression in the art of the townspeople (chōnin) and the austere tradition continuing in Zen institutions and the tea ceremony world. The interaction between these aesthetics produced some of the richest creative tension in Japanese art history.',
