            'The Tokugawa political system achieved its stated goal of stability with remarkable success: 265 years of peace within Japan\'s borders, an extraordinary achievement by any historical standard. But the mechanisms of that stability — rigid class hierarchy, information control, commercial suppression, and isolation — created structural tensions that accumulated over generations. The samurai became an administrative class without wars to fight; the merchants accumulated wealth that their social position could not accommodate; the domains at the margins of the system (particularly the tozama domains of Satsuma and Chōshū) nursed grievances that would eventually power the Meiji Restoration. The architecture of stability was also the architecture of the eventual collapse.',
