            'The Meiji Restoration was arguably the most consequential event in Japanese history: a comprehensive transformation of politics, society, economy, and culture compressed into a few decades. Its success in creating a modern industrial nation-state that could defend itself against Western imperialism — and eventually challenge Western powers militarily — made Japan a model for other Asian nations seeking to modernize without being colonized. But the restoration also created contradictions: a modernizing state built on an archaic imperial mythology, a capitalist economy housed in Confucian social values, a democratic-seeming constitution with a sovereign emperor at its center. Those contradictions would play out across the following century.',
