            'Japan\'s war in China, begun with the Marco Polo Bridge Incident of July 1937 and quickly escalating into full-scale invasion, consumed enormous military and economic resources without decisive resolution. The Nanjing Massacre of December 1937 — in which Japanese forces killed tens of thousands of civilians (Chinese estimates run to 300,000; Japanese scholarly estimates are lower but still catastrophic) — became an international scandal and deepened China\'s resistance. Japan controlled China\'s major cities and coastal regions but could not defeat the Nationalist government, which retreated to Chungking, or suppress Communist guerrillas in the countryside.\n\nThe strategic logic of expansion led Japan deeper into Southeast Asia. After the fall of France in 1940, Japan pressured the Vichy French colonial authorities in Indochina to allow Japanese military access — giving Japan airbases and supply lines for further southern expansion. The United States, alarmed by Japanese expansion and seeking to protect its own position in the Philippines, imposed a series of increasingly severe economic sanctions, culminating in the oil embargo of August 1941. Since Japan imported over 80% of its oil from the United States, the embargo was an ultimatum: withdraw from China and Southeast Asia or face economic strangulation.\n\nThe decision to attack the United States and its allies was made by Japan\'s leadership with full awareness that the odds of long-term success were poor. The calculation was that a swift southern offensive — seizing the oil fields of the Dutch East Indies and surrounding territories — combined with a crippling blow against the US Pacific Fleet at Pearl Harbor, would give Japan a defensible resource empire before American industrial power could be mobilized. It was a strategy of desperation, and its architects knew it. The attack on Pearl Harbor on December 7, 1941 brought the United States into the war; within months Japan had conquered an enormous arc of territory across Southeast Asia and the Pacific.\n\nThe turning point came at Midway (June 1942), where US naval intelligence deciphered Japanese codes and ambushed the attacking Japanese carrier force, sinking four fleet carriers in a single day. From Guadalcanal (1942–43) onward, the US island-hopping campaign systematically dismantled Japan\'s defensive perimeter. American industrial production — factories converting to war production at a rate Japan could not match — produced ships, aircraft, and equipment in quantities that overwhelmed Japanese logistics. By 1944 US bombers were reaching Japan\'s home islands; the firebombing of Tokyo in March 1945 killed more people in a single night than either atomic bomb.\n\nThe atomic bombings of Hiroshima (August 6, 1945) and Nagasaki (August 9, 1945), combined with the Soviet Union\'s declaration of war against Japan on August 8, broke the deadlock within Japan\'s leadership over whether to surrender. Emperor Hirohito\'s unprecedented radio address on August 15, announcing Japan\'s acceptance of the Allied terms, ended the war. Japan had lost approximately 3 million military dead and perhaps 800,000 civilian dead; the broader Asian conflict initiated by Japan had killed far more — estimates of total war deaths attributable to Japan\'s expansion run to 15–30 million across Asia.',
